    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\nYou're writing a program that gives your friend three compliments in a row, but the same message is repeated over and over. That's not very efficient! Instead of copying and pasting the same code, you'll define a function and call it multiple times.\r\n\r\n1. Look at the repeated lines of code that print the same compliment.\r\n\r\n2. Create a function called `give_compliment()` that prints the compliment once.\r\n\r\n3. Replace the repeated code by calling your new function **three times**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nPay close attention to indentation, and use the UMPIRE strategy:\r\n\r\n* **U**nderstand: What's the goal? Why is the repeated code a problem?\r\n\r\n* **M**ake a plan: What will go in the function?\r\n\r\n* **P**roduce: Define the function and replace the repeated lines.\r\n\r\n* **I**nspect: Run it -- does it still give three compliments?\r\n\r\n* **E**xplain: How did using a function improve the code?",
